narratives.question_text: How would you summarize ECON 110 05 for a fellow student? Would you recommend ECON 110 05 to another student? Why or why not?
comments: Don't take it unless you have to. Many people will tell you that. The final was so dam hard I wanted to cry while taking it. Be careful....

Take it if you have to/ want to. Be prepared to be confused and shop around for a great professor. If not, go to a review session with a great professor to help you learn all of those tricky concepts.

As far as I know, there are only two ways to take multivariable calculus at Yale: through Math 120 or ENAS 150. While I did not like Math 120, my friends in ENAS 150 rave about it. I felt as if Math 120 breezed through the material without really focusing on its real world applications (for example, how is finding the volume of a sphere using triple integrals related to economics?). I understand that learning the foundation of the material is very important, but I also believe that being able to apply the material outside of the classroom is key. After taking Math 120, I do not think that that's possible. It failed to engage me, and unless it's a requirement for a major (or if you really love math), I do not recommend that another student takes Math 120. Also, the class' graders are harsh and make me enjoy the class even less when I get my grades back and can't contest them.
